SIMPLE: survey
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Survey
<hw>Sur*vey"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Surveyed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Surveying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>surveoir</ets>, <ets>surveer</ets>; <ets>sur</ets>, <ets>sor</ets>,
over, E. <ets>sur + veoir</ets>, <ets>veeir</ets>, to see, F.
<ets>voir</ets>, L. <ets>videre</ets>. See <er>Sur-</er>, and
<er>Vision</er>, and cf. <er>Supervise</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
inspect, or take a view of; to view with attention, as from a high
place; to overlook; <as>as, to stand on a hill, and <ex>survey</ex> the
surrounding country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Round he <qex>surveys</qex> and well might, where he stood,⟦br⟧
So high above.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To view with a scrutinizing eye; to
examine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With such altered looks, . . . ⟦br⟧
All pale and speechless, he <qex>surveyed</qex> me round.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To examine with reference to condition, situation,
value, etc.; to examine and ascertain the state of; <as>as, to
<ex>survey</ex> a building in order to determine its value and exposure
to loss by fire</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To determine the form, extent, position, etc., of,
as a tract of land, a coast, harbor, or the like, by means of linear and
angular measurements, and the application of the principles of geometry
and trigonometry; <as>as, to <ex>survey</ex> land or a
coast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To examine and ascertain, as the boundaries and
royalties of a manor, the tenure of the tenants, and the rent and value
of the same.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Jacob (Law
Dict.).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Survey</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Survey
<hw>Sur"vey</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly accentuated
universally on the last syllable, and still so accented by many
speakers.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of surveying; a general view,
as from above.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Under his proud <qex>survey</qex> the city lies.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
J. Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A particular view; an examination, especially an
official examination, of all the parts or particulars of a thing, with a
design to ascertain the condition, quantity, or quality; <as>as, a
<ex>survey</ex> of the stores of a ship; a <ex>survey</ex> of roads and
bridges; a <ex>survey</ex> of buildings</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The operation of finding the contour, dimensions,
position, or other particulars of, as any part of the earth's surface,
whether land or water; also, a measured plan and description of any
portion of country, or of a road or line through it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Survey of dogs</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Court of
regard</cref>, under <er>Regard</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Trigonometrical
survey</b></col>, <cd>a survey of a portion of country by measuring a
single base, and connecting it with various points in the tract surveyed
by a series of triangles, the angles of which are carefully measured,
the relative positions and distances of all parts being computed from
these data.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Review; retrospect; examination;
prospect.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surveyal</ent>⟦br⟧
